	url = {http://www.itcon.org/paper/2019/15},
	abstract = {There has been considerable interest in Building Information Modeling ({BIM}) research and development during the last decade. {BIM} has established itself as a field of research in (and beyond) scientific communities interested in information technologies in construction. Interestingly, the contours of {BIM} as a scientific field are still not clearly identified. Several studies have recently tried to analyze different aspects of this issue, without providing a systematic and comprehensive methodological approach to accurately define the major themes and clusters of the {BIM} domain. This paper uses a systematic literature review approach to map the {BIM} research themes and clusters over ten years of scientific publications. 1244 articles published in peer-reviewed journals between 2007 and 2016 were selected and the associated metadata analyzed in order to highlight co-occurrences in author’s keywords. It appears that a few “big players” dominate the keywords, while most of the keywords used by authors are much less cited. Seven core clusters are identified using modularity optimization techniques: industry foundation classes, information technology, facility management, building, collaboration, computer aided design, and laser scanning.},
