	abstract = {Buildings are increasingly equipped with data monitoring infrastructures to collect multiple layers of dynamic data pertaining to the states and events related to systems’ performance, indoor-environmental conditions, occupants’ location, movement, and control-oriented actions representation of dynamic building related data. Efficiently utilized, this data could not only enhance the quality and effectiveness of buildings’ operational regimes, but also enrich the knowledge base for building design decision support. However, to exploit the potential of this data effectively, seamless data transformation processes are needed, starting from raw monitoring data and ending in adequately structured and visualized building performance data. In the present contribution, we provide a detailed blueprint of a well-defined and ontologically supported instance of such a transformation process. To illustrate this process, we focus in this paper on a specific class of building performance queries that require information on buildings’ visually relevant boundary conditions. Such queries pertain to, for example, the intensity of incident solar radiation of buildings’ envelope components, the daylight availability and 114distribution in interior spaces, and the expected output of building-integrated solar energy harvesting systems.},
