	abstract = {We present a new approach and a prototype software engine for defeasible reasoning to support automated building code compliance checking. The challenge with formalising defeasible rules in a purely deductive reasoning system is the resulting exponential blow up of the rule set due to the need to explicitly state numerous combinations of exception cases. This leads to a rule set that is brittle, complicated, difficult to understand, and obscures the central point of a given normative provision. Moreover, assessing compliance, to any degree, in the absence of complete information about a building, down to the smallest detail, is very limited in a purely deductive setting in which nothing can be assumed. We empirically evaluate our prototype reasoning engine on an {IFC} model of a building in Christchurch, New Zealand, for compliance with accessibility criteria from the New Zealand Building Code.},
