	abstract = {As the mounting demand for building new residential and commercial units strikes the record, significant pressure from stakeholders investing in the construction industry has increasingly been requiring the government authorities to issue the construction permit in a timely manner. However, the architectural and engineering design review process is still mostly a time-consuming manual procedure. It involves assessing a design against codes and standards requirements to validate the accuracy and quality of the design and detecting errors before manufacturing and fabrication commences. Building design provisions are generally in the form of texts, charts, tables, and mathematical expressions. These regulations and guidelines usually have legal status. Thus, the computerization of this process represents a real challenge to the Architecture, Engineering, and Construction ({AEC}) industry. Building Information Modeling ({BIM}) provides a platform for developing a virtual permitting process to improve the efficacy of issuing building permits by the authorities. This chapter reviews recent advancements in virtual permitting using {BIM}. Also, it presents data collected about the construction permitting process from Authority Having Jurisdiction ({AHJ}) plan reviewers, architects, engineers, and general contractors in the state of Florida. The primary goal is to tackle the problem by using the available data and technology to develop a {BIM}-driven Virtual Permitting System ({VPS}) to achieve design accuracy and permitting efficiency. The potential integration of {VPS} with blockchain will be discussed, along with benefits and limitations.},
